#42 2021.0  * Messages for package app-emulation/qemu-10.2.0-r1:
#42 2021.0 
#42 2021.0  * If you don't have kvm compiled into the kernel, make sure you have the
#42 2021.0  * kernel module loaded before running kvm. The easiest way to ensure that the
#42 2021.0  * kernel module is loaded is to load it on boot.
#42 2021.0  * For AMD CPUs the module is called 'kvm-amd'.
#42 2021.0  * For Intel CPUs the module is called 'kvm-intel'.
#42 2021.0  * Please review /etc/conf.d/modules for how to load these.
#42 2021.0  * Make sure your user is in the 'kvm' group. Just run
#42 2021.0  * # gpasswd -a <USER> kvm
#42 2021.0  * then have <USER> re-login.
#42 2021.0  * For brand new installs, the default permissions on /dev/kvm might not let
#42 2021.0  * you access it.  You can tell udev to reset ownership/perms:
#42 2021.0  * # udevadm trigger -c add /dev/kvm
#42 2021.0  * If you want to register binfmt handlers for qemu user targets:
#42 2021.0  * For openrc:
#42 2021.0  * # rc-update add qemu-binfmt
#42 2021.0  * For systemd:
#42 2021.0  * # ln -s /usr/share/qemu/binfmt.d/qemu.conf /etc/binfmt.d/qemu.conf
#42 2021.0  * (Note: Above message is only printed the first time package is
#42 2021.0  * installed. Please look at /usr/share/doc/qemu-10.2.0-r1/README.gentoo*
#42 2021.0  * for future reference)
